body:
Crowley: Listen up, big guy. I got three good reasons why you should just walk away. Number one: [points at Azriaphale] Look at that guy! He’s got that sissy, stringy, music thing.

Aziraphale: We’ve been through this. It’s a harp, and you know it.

Crowley: All right. So, that’s a harp… and that’s a dress!

Aziraphale: Robe!

Crowley: Reason number two: *flips into a one handed handstand*

Human: But, uh, what does that have to do with anything?

Aziraphale: No, no, he’s got a point.

summary: crowley’s not all that stupid, if we’re being honest -- sure, he’s not much of one for books, certainly doesn’t have the time to...
body:
crowley’s not all that stupid, if we’re being honest – sure, he’s not much of one for books, certainly doesn’t have the time to waste on something he deems so trivial, but he does have the wherewithall to handle himself. he’s smart in a practical sort of way, able to stand up against the big bad world, able to come up with clever plans and weave intricate lies and think on his feet. 

aziraphale isn’t stupid, either – he’s foolish, perhaps, too trusting and kind for his own good, and often in trouble for his rather bumbling nature. but he loves to read, to learn. he owns an antique book store whose business model hinges upon him not actually selling any books because he just wants to own them all. he studies prophecies, quotes authors at the drop of a hat.

now, traditionally speaking, if you add crowley’s single, streetsmart braincell to zira’s single, scholarly braincell, the result ought to be two braincells in total. that is how math tends to work, after all.

and yet, bafflingly, when you put these two dumbasses in a room together, they manage to misplace both of their collective braincells and just spend the entire time looking at each other as if they are so desperately, hopelessly in love with each other that they might just evaporate on the spot???? someone who understands math please explain

tags: every queen song in good omens but
summary: Every Queen song in Good Omens but
body:
Every Queen song in Good Omens but

OneRepublic


More compiled by @the-bentley-mixtapes

  1. Bohemian Rhapsody (Crowley’s Entrance)- Everybody Loves Me- well hell sees her shadow in my backseat/ and her friends are standing right in front of me/ world wide from the Cimmaron to Turkey/ open up said everybody loves me
  2. These Are the Days of Our Lives- Aziraphale and Crowley driving- Counting Stars- I’m old, but I’m not that old/ young, but I’m not that bold/ and I don’t think the world is sold/ I’m just doing what we’re told/ I feel something so right/ doing the wrong thing/ I feel something so wrong/ doing the right thing
  3. Bicycle Race- hitting Anathema- I Lived- I owned every second that this world could give/ saw so many places, the things that I did/ and with every broken bone/ I swear I lived
  4. You’re My Best Friend- Crowley arriving at the bookstore- Marching On- there’s so many wars we fought/ so many things we’re not/ but with what we have/ I promise you that/ we’re marchin’ on, we’re marchin’ on, we’re marchin’ on
  5. Somebody to Love- Crowley leaving the bookstore- Mercy- angel of mercy, how did you find me/ where did you read my story?/ pulled from the papers, desperate and hurting/ seeking a momentary fix/ all I wanted to say, all I wanted to do/ has fallen apart now/ all I wanted to feel, I wanted to love/ it’s all my fault now
  6. Another One Bites the Dust- Crowley in traffic- Au Revoir- today I’m not myself/ and you, you’re someone else/ and all these rules don’t fit/ and all that starts can quit/ what a peculiar state we’re in/ what a peculiar state we’re in
  7. I’m In Love with My Car- The M25- Fear- when we were children we’d play/ out in the streets just tempting fate/ when we were children we’d say/ that we don’t know the meaning of fear
  8. We Will Rock You- Crowley’s airbase entrance- Secrets- ‘till my sleeves are stained red/ with all the truth that I’ve said/ came by it honestly I swear/ thought you saw me blink no/ I’ve been on the brink so
  9. Lazing on a Sunday Afternoon- Crowley and Aziraphale at the park- Life in Color- you’ve seen my worst/ yet you see some hope in me/ the black and white sets us free/ like the queen to the rook your decision is a sure thing/ honey yeah a sure thing/ no wonder I feel/ like I’m missing a heavy load

BONUS: A Nightingale Sang in Berkeley Square- Heaven- when the room don’t like us/ I’ll be at your table/ yeah I’ll be sitting next to you/ and when the world ain’t righteous/ it’s raining Cain and Abels/ I’ll be trying to dance with you

summary: I have this headcanon that Aziraphale sometimes uses the computer in his shop to write up precise and articulate reviews of...
body:
I have this headcanon that Aziraphale sometimes uses the computer in his shop to write up precise and articulate reviews of books, then publishes them on his Internet Journal (“I refuse to call it a blog, Crowley.”). He’s amassed quite a literary following and is very proud.

Crowley responds by setting up a YouTube channel and posting drunken book reviews. He, of course, does not read books, so each video is him consuming glass after glass of wine and shouting about book-to-movie adaptations as though he has read the book.

Aziraphale hates it, but he watches every video.

body:
listen I played myself. “A Good Omens-based garashir AU practically writes itself,” I said. 

Now I’m deeply invested in this and I can’t decide which one of them is the angel and which is the demon.

Although actually, considering the spirit of the source material, that’s probably a good sign.

points for Bashir as the angel and Garak as the demon:

  • Bashir is from the Federation, and the Federation can be very Good Omens heaven tbh.
  • he can be, uhh… preachy. He heals things for a living.
  • Garak is from the Obsidian Order. They uh. Are kind of. “Love, bad. Kill people, good.” Funny old world, if Obsidian Order agents went around trusting each other.
  • He. Literally. Is a scaly reptile creature in vaguely human form and the place he hails from is dark and hot.

On the other hand!

Points for Garak as the angel and Bashir as the demon:

  • Garak owns a shop. He has a public identity that is extremely equated with his shop. There’s a lot of other stuff behind that, but the public identity is important to him.
  • Books! Food! Alcohol! Richly detailed, warm and comfortable-looking clothing!
  • Speaks in a slightly more formal mode. Sometimes even slightly stiff.
  • Bashir… saunters.
  • He’s the one who makes an effort to be suave, and the one who seeks out speed and excitement. He’s the one who’s always up on the latest tech. He likes to think that he is Cool.

Anyway

if I did write this I would probably go for angel!Bashir and demon!Garak because those are more logistics points and the second list is more about personality

so I sort of picture it being more like a “what if there was an angel like Crowley and a demon like Aziraphale” AU

I probably won’t write it though, I have very little time and energy to spare!

@tinsnip would you like to contribute ideas, write this, or attempt to convince me to write this?
